# Chapter 02 — Working with Text Files and Streams

---

# Chapter Overview

Text files are the heart of Linux.

Unlike many operating systems that rely heavily on graphical interfaces and binary configuration files, Linux stores an enormous amount of information as plain text.

System administrators spend a large portion of their day reading logs, editing configuration files, searching for specific information, comparing files, redirecting output, and combining commands together.

Mastering text processing is one of the biggest milestones in becoming comfortable with Linux.

By the end of this chapter, you'll understand not only how to work with text files, but also how Linux treats everything as a stream of data that can be manipulated with simple yet powerful commands.

