# Why Text Matters in Linux

Most important Linux files are plain text.

Examples include:

```text
/etc/passwd
/etc/group
/etc/hosts
/etc/fstab
/etc/ssh/sshd_config
```

Log files:

```text
/var/log/syslog
/var/log/auth.log
```

Configuration files:

```text
*.conf
*.cfg
*.ini
```

Scripts:

```bash
.sh
```

Because everything is stored as text, Linux provides powerful tools to manipulate it.

---

# The Linux Stream Philosophy

One of Linux's greatest ideas is that almost everything is treated as a stream.

```text
Application
      │
      ▼
 Standard Output
      │
      ▼
Another Command
      │
      ▼
File
```

Programs usually don't know where their output goes.

It may be:

- Your terminal
- A file
- Another command
- A network connection

This flexibility is what makes Linux so powerful.

---

# Standard Streams

Every Linux program starts with three standard communication channels.

```text
           Program
        ┌─────────────┐
stdin → │             │
stdout← │             │
stderr← │             │
        └─────────────┘
```

| Stream | Number | Purpose |
|----------|---------|----------|
| stdin | 0 | Input |
| stdout | 1 | Normal output |
| stderr | 2 | Error output |

These three streams form the foundation of shell scripting and command pipelines.

